Package com.rb.nonbiz.collections

Class RBEnumMap<E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​V>

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.collections.RBEnumMap<E,​V>
public class RBEnumMap<E extends java.lang.Enum<E>,​V>
extends java.lang.Object
Similar to EnumMap. However, it is meant to be immutable. So this is more like an RBMap, but specialized for enum keys.

Always prefer RBEnumMap to EnumMap, especially on an interface, but even inside a method's body, when possible. Here's why:

Guava ImmutableMap implements the Map interface, but its put() method will throw at runtime. However, RBEnumMap intentionally has NO methods to modify it. That offers compile-time safety.

Another advantage: a regular Map.get(Object) returns null if the value is not there. We don't like nulls in the codebase, plus that behavior is confusing to someone new to Java.

Instead, RBEnumMap has:

  1. getOptional(Enum) (which will return an Optional.empty() if there is no value for the specified key).
  2. getOrThrow(Enum), which assumes the value is there, and returns Optional.of(...).
See Also:
RBEnumMaps, RBEnumMapSimpleConstructors
